    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2726676428" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2726676428" />
    <a title="Faith Justice" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4243191-faith-justice"><img alt="Faith Justice" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442509839p2/4243191.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2726676428?book_show_action=true">May 05, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Faith Justice" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Faith Justice" href="/user/show/4243191-faith-justice">Faith Justice</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4243191-faith-justice?shelf=ebook">ebook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4243191-faith-justice?shelf=research">research</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2726676428" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1338299098719086017">As part of my research into the early development of the Christian Church, I took an online course &quot;How Jesus Became God&quot; by Dr. Ehrman, which I very much enjoyed. When this book showed up as an eBook bargain, I got it and promptly lost it on my huge digital TBR shelf. It surfaced when I needed to do more research and I found it immensely helpful. <br/><br/>Ehrman does a good job covering the history of the developing Bible from it&apos;s earliest roots to more recent versions, through translations from and in</span>
  <span id="freeText1338299098719086017" style="display:none">As part of my research into the early development of the Christian Church, I took an online course "How Jesus Became God" by Dr. Ehrman, which I very much enjoyed. When this book showed up as an eBook bargain, I got it and promptly lost it on my huge digital TBR shelf. It surfaced when I needed to do more research and I found it immensely helpful. <br /><br />Ehrman does a good job covering the history of the developing Bible from it's earliest roots to more recent versions, through translations from and into several ancient languages, and historical "editing" to make the stories fit with current (at the time) religious beliefs. He explains the academic field that tries to get back to the "original" texts with tested techniques and standards of practice and evaluates the success (or lack thereof) of various scholarly efforts to resolve contradictions in the New Testament. <br /><br />It's a dense and difficult read, filled with footnotes. It's not geared to the casual reader. However, anyone with an interest in knowing where the Bible came from and how it evolved will find it fascinating. He doesn't get into the original choices made by the early Church to include some texts and exclude others when they put the New Testament together, but deals with those included and how and why they have changed over time.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1338299098719086017" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

